    https://litmus.com/blog Litmus Company Blog Wed, 16 Mar 2016 18:34:55
   +0000 en-US hourly 1 http://wordpress.org/?v=4.2.4
   https://litmus.com/blog/how-to-track-post-click-visitor-engagement-in-y
   our-next-email
   https://litmus.com/blog/how-to-track-post-click-visitor-engagement-in-y
   our-next-email#comments Wed, 16 Mar 2016 18:32:30 +0000 Lauren Smith
   Features & Updates Tips & Resources analytics campaign performance data
   google analytics litmus builder post-click tracking subscriber
   engagement tracking manager utm utm codes utm parameters
   https://litmus.com/blog/?p=11987 <p>While your email service provider
   is full of great metrics like open, click, and spam rates, thereôs
   likely a gap in subscriber engagement. What do your subscribers do
   after theyôve clicked through to your website? What pages are they
   visiting on your site? Do they spend time on a particular page, or do
   they bounce immediately? Are they purchasing anything? By adding
   tracking to your links you can answer these questionsîand moreîfor a full
   picture of your email campaign success. </p> <p>The post <a
   rel="nofollow"
   href="https://litmus.com/blog/how-to-track-post-click-visitor-engagemen
   t-in-your-next-email">How to Track Post-Click Visitor Engagement In
   Your Next Email</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow"
   href="https://litmus.com/blog">Litmus Blog</a>.</p> <p>How do you
   measure the success of an email campaign?</p> <p>While your email
   service provider is full of great metrics like open, click, and spam
   rates, thereôs likely a gap in subscriber engagement.</p> <p>What do
   your subscribers do <em>after</em> theyôve clicked through to your
   website? </p> <p>What pages are they visiting on your site? Do they
   spend time on a particular page, or do they bounce immediately? Are
   they purchasing anything? </p> <p>Good marketers can accurately measure
   results. Great ones can attribute activity downstreamîdownloads, sales,
   etc,îto the specific activities that drive them.</p> <p>By adding
   tracking to your links you can answer these questionsîand moreîfor a full
   picture of your email campaign success. </p> <div class="cta"> <table>
   <tbody> <tr> <td class="block-1"> <img
   src="https://d31v04zdn5vmni.cloudfront.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016
   /03/tracking-manager.png"> </td> <td class="block-2"> <h2>Tracking
   Manager in Litmus Builder</h2> <p>Automatically add tracking codes to
   links in your emails. Tracking your subscribers post-click has never
   been easier or quicker.</p> <p class="zero"><a
   href="https://litmus.com/email-builder?utm_campaign=tracking_manager&#0
   38;utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog&#038;utm_content=top"
   target="_blank" class="btn medium orange button">Add post-click
   tracking í</a></p> </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> </div> <p>&nbsp;</p>
   <h2>How do I add post-click tracking to my email campaigns?</h2>
   <p>While post-click tracking will vary based on the web analytics
   tracking tool youôre using, weôll cover the one of the most popularîGoogle
   Analyticsîin this post.</p> <p>If youôre using Google Analytics, you can
   track your subscribersô post-click activities by adding UTM codes to the
   end of the URLs in your email. Also known as UTM parameters, UTM codes
   are bits of text added to the end of your URL to help you track user
   behavior on your website.</p> <p>If youôve ever been to a website, or
   hovered over a text link, and noticed a URL like the one below,
   it&#8217;s likely because UTM codes are being used.</p>
   <pre><code>https://litmus.com/email-builder?utm_campaign=tracking_manag
   er_launch&#038;utm_source=pardot&#038;utm_medium=email&#038;utm_content
   =image1</code></pre> <p>In the example above, youôll see the website
   address (<strong>https://litmus.com/email-builder</strong>), and then a
   snippet of text after the question mark. The snippet of text following
   the website address are the UTM codes.</p> <p>Adding UTM codes to your
   links wonôt break your links. Instead, they give you access to data that
   goes beyond the opens and clicks provided by your ESP. </p> <p>Each
   portion of the UTM code tracks a different aspect of the traffic on
   your website:</p> <ul> <li><strong>Campaign Name</strong>
   <em><strong>(utm_campaign=tracking_manager_launch)</strong></em>: Use
   this to identify a specific product promotion or campaign. In the
   example above, the campaign is útracking_managerù which means the focus
   of the email campaign was the <a
   href="https://litmus.com/help/testing/litmus-builder-guide?utm_campaign
   =tracking_manager&#038;utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog#track
   ing-manager">Tracking Manager</a> launch.</li> <li><strong>Campaign
   Source</strong> <em><strong>(utm_source=pardot)</strong></em>: The
   campaign source should cover where your traffic is coming to the site
   from. In the example above, the email was sent via Pardot so that is
   the source. If your content was shared via Twitter, for instance, you
   would use &#8220;twitter&#8221; as your source.</li>
   <li><strong>Campaign Medium</strong>
   <em><strong>(utm_medium=email)</strong></em>: Use the campaign medium
   to take a high-level look at your marketing efforts. In the example
   above, the medium is simply úemail.ù Youôll be able to track all of your
   general email marketing efforts, but then can drill down into the
   source and name to get detailed data on specific campaigns.</li>
   <li><strong>Campaign Content</strong>
   <em><strong>(utm_content=image1)</strong></em>: While not a required
   UTM code, campaign content is a great way to dig deeper into your data.
   You can use them to specify text links, CTA buttons, and even linked
   images to see which types of CTAs generate not only the most clicks
   (you can see that in your ESPôs data), but what types of CTAs encourage
   the most post-click activities.</li> </ul> <p>The use of these UTM code
   elements varies based on how you want your information displayed in
   Google Analytics. In the example above, we have the medium as the
   highest level of organization, followed by source, name, and content.
   How you organize yours is up to you!</p>
   <p><em><strong>Note</strong></em><em>: UTM codes are case sensitive!
   So, úPardotù and úpardotù would both be separated in Google Analytics
   reports. Be consistent when it comes to capitalization to avoid any
   confusions.</em></p> <h3>Creating UTM codes</h3> <p>There are numerous
   ways to create UTM codes: using Googleôs URL builder tool, manually
   writing them, or using an internal customized tool. </p> <h4>Google URL
   builder</h4> <p>Google has a <a
   href="https://support.google.com/analytics/answer/1033867">free
   tool</a> for creating URLs with UTM codes on them. You plug in your
   URL, and the numerous UTM codes and a link will be generated for
   you.</p> <h4>Manually writing them</h4> <p>While time consuming, itôs
   possible to manually add UTM codes to each of your URLs once youôve
   memorized the formula. However, creating them yourself definitely
   leaves room for error.</p> <h4>Internal tool</h4> <p>Keeping track of
   UTM codes can be a bit unwieldy depending on how many campaigns youôre
   running. If you have an awesome dev team (we definitely do!), then you
   can create a tool of your own to manage your UTM creation.</p> <figure
   id="post-12001 media-12001" class="alignnone"><img class=""
   src="https://d31v04zdn5vmni.cloudfront.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016
   /03/utm-tool.png" alt="UTM tool - post-click tracking" /></figure>
   <p>While time consuming from a dev perspective, this internal tool has
   been a great way for us to create and organize our UTM codes.</p>
   <h3>Adding UTM codes to your campaigns</h3> <p>So what do you do after
   you have your UTM codes for a campaign? Itôs time to add them to the
   links in your campaign. </p> <h4>Manually adding them</h4> <p>You can
   manually add your UTM codes at the end of every link in your campaign.
   Simply search your email for URLs linking to your site, and add the
   codes to the end of the URLs. </p> <p>While this is definitely an
   option, itôs time consuming, and leaves room for errors, such as missing
   links.</p> <h4>Some Email service providers can do it for you</h4>
   <p>Many ESPs support automated link tracking. For example, <a
   href="http://help.campaignmonitor.com/topic.aspx?t=111&#038;_ga=1.78721
   620.1733968664.1396275600">Campaign Monitor has a Google Analytics
   integration</a>. Once users link their accounts together, they enter
   the domains they want to track (ie. ours would be litmus.com), as well
   as the campaign source. </p> <p>Campaign names are automatically pulled
   from the name of the campaign in Campaign Monitor, and the medium is
   set to email. Neither of these aspects can be edited by the user. The
   UTM codes are then added to every link on the domain(s) selected during
   the integration. </p> <p>While automated link tracking by ESPs is a big
   time saver, you donôt have the flexibility to edit campaign names to
   your preference. </p> <h4>Tracking Manager in Litmus Builder</h4>
   <p>With Tracking Manager in Litmus Builder, adding tracking codes to
   links in your email has never been quicker or easier. </p> <p>Say
   goodbye to the hassle of copying your tracking code, endlessly
   scrolling or searching for every single link the email, and pasting the
   tracking code to each link. And now you can customize your UTM codes to
   suit your tracking preferences.</p> <p>Simply input your tracking code,
   and select which links in the email youôd like to apply it to. </p>
   <figure id="post-12003 media-12003" class="alignnone"><img class=""
   src="https://d31v04zdn5vmni.cloudfront.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016
   /03/builder-tracking-manager-1000x872.png" alt="builder tracking
   manager - post-click tracking" /></figure> <p>Every link you select
   will have the UTM codes automatically added to the end of it.</p>
   <p>Want to include campaign content for specific links? Create unique
   tracking codes for those specific links, and Tracking Manager will
   automatically add them in. </p> <p>Want more details about how it
   works? Check out our <a
   href="https://litmus.com/help/testing/litmus-builder-guide?utm_campaign
   =tracking_manager&#038;utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog#track
   ing-manager">help documentation</a>, or explainer video below:</p>
   <p><script charset="ISO-8859-1"
   src="//fast.wistia.com/assets/external/E-v1.js" async></script> <div
   class="wistia_embed wistia_async_t21wknd2uf"
   style="height:304px;width:540px">&nbsp;</div> <p> <p>Tracking Manager
   in Litmus Builder is now active in all Litmus accounts. Donôt have a
   Builder account yet? <a
   href="https://litmus.com/email-builder?utm_campaign=tracking_manager&#0
   38;utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog&#038;utm_content=textlink
   ">Sign up todayîitôs free</a>!</p> <h2>How do I look at my emailôs
   post-click performance?</h2> <p>Once your campaign has been sent, itôs
   time to start analyzing the post-click activities within your analytics
   software. In our example, we used Google URL tracking, so weôll cover
   how to look at reports in Google Analytics. </p> <p>Navigate to úAll
   Campaignsù under úAcquisition.ù The campaigns listed here are not email
   specificîthey cover campaigns across all channels. Change the reportôs
   primary dimension to úmediumù to focus just on email results.</p> <figure
   id="post-12006 media-12006" class="alignnone"><img class=""
   src="https://d31v04zdn5vmni.cloudfront.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016
   /03/google-analytics-medium-report.png" alt="google analytics medium
   report" /></figure> <p>Then, click on úemailù and then add úcampaignù as a
   secondary dimension to receive a list of all of your email campaigns to
   compare against one another. </p> <figure id="post-12007 media-12007"
   class="alignnone"><img class=""
   src="https://d31v04zdn5vmni.cloudfront.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016
   /03/google-analytics-medium-and-campaign-report.png" alt="google
   analytics medium and campaign report" /></figure> <p>This report
   includes all campaigns under the email medium. You can see pageviews,
   new users, bounce rates, and more. </p> <p>If you have goals set up in
   Google Analyticsîlike newsletter signups, trial signups, paid signups,
   etc.îyou can also see how many people from a specific campaign completed
   one of those goals.</p> <p>Did one campaign outshine the others in
   terms of sessions, and goal completions? Take a look at how that
   campaign differs from others and make educated decisions about how to
   improve future campaigns. </p> <h3>Want to see how email stacks up
   against other channels?</h3> <p>To compare email performance versus
   other channels, navigate to úChannelsù under úAcquisition.ù</p> <figure
   id="post-12008 media-12008" class="alignnone"><img class=""
   src="https://d31v04zdn5vmni.cloudfront.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016
   /03/google-analytics-channel-report.png" alt="google analytics channel
   report - post-click tracking" /></figure> <p>Within this report, youôll
   be able to see the performance across all channels that bring traffic
   to your siteîorganic search, referral traffic, email, etc. You can see
   how each channel measures up in terms of pageviews, new users, and
   goals that youôve set up. This is the perfect place to show the power of
   email! </p> <h3>Looking for more tips on analyzing your campaign
   performance in Google Analytics?</h3> <p>Check out Campaign Monitorôs
   post, ú<a
   href="https://www.campaignmonitor.com/blog/email-marketing/2014/08/meas
   ure-email-marketing-google-analytics/">3 Steps to Measure the Success
   of Your Email Marketing with Google Analytics</a>.ù Smart Insight also
   has a great post on <a
   href="http://www.smartinsights.com/email-marketing/email-marketing-anal
   ytics/email-campaign-tracking-with-google-analytics/">creating Advanced
   segments</a> in Google Analytics to isolate visitors from email so you
   can report on just your email traffic. </p> <div class="cta"> <table>
   <tbody> <tr> <td class="block-1"> <img
   src="https://d31v04zdn5vmni.cloudfront.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016
   /03/tracking-manager.png"> </td> <td class="block-2"> <h2>Tracking
   Manager in Litmus Builder</h2> <p>Automatically add tracking codes to
   links in your emails. Tracking your subscribers post-click has never
   been easier or quicker.</p> <p class="zero"><a
   href="https://litmus.com/email-builder?utm_campaign=tracking_manager&#0
   38;utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog&#038;utm_content=bottom"
   target="_blank" class="btn medium orange button">Add post-click
   tracking í</a></p> </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> </div> <p>&nbsp;</p>
