   https://litmus.com/blog/?p=11872 <p>At Litmus, we strive not just to
   make email better, but to make ourselves better. We pride ourselves on
   our culture of collaboration and creativity (we even won an award for
   it!), and our relentless focus on our customers (you guys!). We take
   immense pride in our company culture even as we grow. Peek inside one
   of our favorite weeks of the year and see what it's like to be a Litmus
   employee!</p> <p>The post <a rel="nofollow"
   href="https://litmus.com/blog/litmus-culture-2016-annual-team-retreat">
   Peek Inside Litmus Culture: 2016 Annual Team Retreat</a> appeared first
   on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://litmus.com/blog">Litmus
   Blog</a>.</p> <p>At Litmus, we strive not just to make email better,
   but to make ourselves better. We pride ourselves on our culture of
   collaboration and creativity (<a
   href="https://litmus.com/blog/were-a-2014-best-places-to-work-winner?ut
   m=culture_stowe16&#038;utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog">we
   even won an award for it!</a>), and our relentless focus on our
   customers (you guys!). Weôve grown dramatically since last year, nearly
   doubling the number of people behind the magic with 24 new
   employees.</p> <p>With that, weôve added talent from all corners of the
   globe. Our úremote firstù culture allows us to be humans first and
   employees second. We get to watch our kids act in school plays, go for
   a quick run, refrain from putting on pants in the morning if we want
   to, or indulge our wanderlust, as long as we get our jobs done. And
   though thatôs awesome, thereôs no substitute for face-to-face
   bonding.</p> <p>úI love that weôre remote first,ù says Paul Farnell,
   Co-founder and CEO of Litmus. úItôs opened us up to talent we never would
   have seen otherwise. Staying connectedîwhether thatôs through Slack,
   video conferencing, or frequent callsîis one of our challenges, and I
   think weôve all really embraced that challenge.ù</p> <p>We just spent
   some time coming together as a team at our annual company retreatîfrom
   as far away as Pakistan and Ecuadorîto reconnect, recharge, and
   ultimately re-inspire ourselves and our teammates. We whiteboarded,
   presented, chatted, and skied together to remind ourselves who we are
   and what matters most to us. </p> <blockquote><p> úEverything we do is
   as a team. Weôre always seeking to improve ourselves and celebrate the
   accomplishments as a group effort. Our semi-annual company-wide meetups
   are my favorite way we do that.ù &#8211;Paul Farnell </p></blockquote>
