   https://litmus.com/blog/this-month-in-community-emoji-email-to-fall-in-
   love-with#comments Mon, 29 Feb 2016 17:00:04 +0000 Jason Rodriguez
   Community community community contest emoji responsive framework
   https://litmus.com/blog/?p=11770 <p>The Litmus Community is the place
   for email designers and marketers to discuss their craft, talk about
   industry news, and join in the (occasional) controversial rant and
   discussion.</p> <p>In case you havenôt been keeping up, hereôs what
   happened this month in the Community.</p> <p>The post <a rel="nofollow"
   href="https://litmus.com/blog/this-month-in-community-emoji-email-to-fa
   ll-in-love-with">This Month in Community: Emoji + Email to Fall in Love
   With</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow"
   href="https://litmus.com/blog">Litmus Blog</a>.</p> <p>The <a
   href="https://litmus.com/community?utm_campaign=community_feb2016&#038;
   utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog">Litmus Community</a> is the
   place for email designers and marketers to discuss their craft, talk
   about industry news, and join in the (occasional) controversial rant
   and discussion. </p> <p>In case you havenôt been keeping up, hereôs what
   happened this month in the Community.</p> <h2>A New Responsive
   Framework</h2> <p>Community member Nicolas Garnier <a
   href="https://litmus.com/community/discussions/4798-mjml-the-only-frame
   work-that-makes-responsive-email-easy?utm_campaign=community_feb2016&#0
   38;utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog">dropped a bomb</a> when
   he announced a new framework for easily building responsive emails, <a
   href="http://mjml.io/">MJML</a>. The framework, which was built
   in-house at Mailjet, abstracts away a lot of the complexity of building
   responsive emails and provides prebuilt components for quickly
   developing campaigns. Itôs one of a few frameworks trying to modernize
   how we develop email campaigns and is a breath of fresh air for many a
   frustrated designer. Check it out and <a
   href="https://litmus.com/community/discussions/4798-mjml-the-only-frame
   work-that-makes-responsive-email-easy?utm_campaign=community_feb2016&#0
   38;utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog">give Nicolas
   feedback</a> in the Community. </p> <h2>Emoji in Email</h2> <p>Melissa
   McCollum <a
   href="https://litmus.com/community/discussions/4879-emoji-and-unicode-s
   tandards-across-platforms?utm_campaign=community_feb2016&#038;utm_sourc
   e=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog">posed a few questions</a> about the
   use of emoji in email. After noticing that different platforms display
   different emoji, she was curious about how others handled the
   situation. How do you keep emoji consistent across platforms? And where
   is the best place to use emoji? <a
   href="https://litmus.com/community/discussions/4879-emoji-and-unicode-s
   tandards-across-platforms?utm_campaign=community_feb2016&#038;utm_sourc
   e=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog">Let her know your thoughts</a>.</p>
   <h2>Email in 2020</h2> <p>Inspired by our recent <a
   href="https://litmus.com/lp/email-marketing-in-2020?utm_campaign=commun
   ity_feb2016&#038;utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog">Email
   Marketing in 2020</a> report, I <a
   href="https://litmus.com/community/discussions/4862-what-will-email-mar
   keting-look-like-in-the-year-2020?utm_campaign=community_feb2016&#038;u
   tm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog">put the question</a> to the
   Community:</p> <blockquote><p>What will email marketing look like in
   2020?</p></blockquote> <p>So far, the consensus seems to be that
   context and delivering the right content at the right time will be a
   key to email success in the coming years. Weôd love to hear what you
   think. Will our tools change dramatically? How will content differ in
   four years? Will automation rule our industry? <a
   href="https://litmus.com/community/discussions/4862-what-will-email-mar
   keting-look-like-in-the-year-2020?utm_campaign=community_feb2016&#038;u
   tm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog">Weigh in</a> on the
   Community discussion. </p> <h2>Emails to Fall in Love With</h2> <p>In
   our <a
   href="https://litmus.com/community/discussions/4777-community-contest-d
   esign-an-email-to-fall-in-love-with?utm_campaign=community_feb2016&#038
   ;utm_source=litmusblog&#038;utm_medium=blog">latest Community
   Contest</a>, we challenged people to push the envelope of Valentineôs
   Day designs. As with most of our contests, we were blown away. While
   there were only a few entries, they did a great job of breaking free
   from Cupidôs typically cute chains. </p> <p>Community members Paul Airy
   and Sophia George both delivered beautifully designed Valentineôs Day
   emails. We especially loved Paulôs patented úLove òOô Meterù. In the end, we
   had to crown the tag team of Miah Roberts and Camille Palu the winners
   with their úLove Uù email. </p> <figure style="margin: -20px -30px 15px
   -100px;"><script type="text/javascript"
   src="https://litmus.com/builder/embed/v1.js" class="builder-embed"
   data-token="e0e94c9"></script></figure> <p>Miah and Camôs email takes
   pixel art animation to a whole new level. Meticulously coded tables
   provide the foundation for some nice CSS animations to deliver a stark
   and entertaining Valentineôs Day email unlike any weôve seen before. </p>
