Webmail Increases to 29% for November Email Client Market Share

   [ 0 By Kayla Voigt

   Every month, we track opens from more than 1 billion emails using
   Litmus‚Äô Email Analytics and share the trends we observe in various
   email clients and environments. In November, webmail market share grew
   to 29%, while mobile and desktop dropped to 55% and 16%, respectively.
   nov16emailmarketshare.001

A REFRESHER ON MARKET SHARE TERMS + EMAIL OPENS

     * ‚ÄúMobile‚Äù refers not only to mobile-specific email clients, like
       iPhone or Android, but also where users are opening their email. If
       they‚Äôre using the Yahoo Mail app on their iPhone, for example, that
       counts as a mobile open for iPhone. This also includes tablets like
       the iPad.
     * ‚ÄúDesktop‚Äù shows any email client opened on a desktop application.
       That means any email client that required you to install software.
       If you‚Äôre using a Mac, for instance, that could mean Apple Mail. On
       a PC, that might be Outlook.
     * ‚ÄúWebmail,‚Äù by contrast, means you‚Äôre using an email client within a
       browser. Logging onto your Gmail account or using Outlook.com fall
       under the ‚Äúwebmail‚Äù category.

   How do we track opens? Open tracking in Litmus Email Analytics is based
   on 1√ó1 invisible pixel image tracking, which is the same technique that
   your email service provider uses to report your
   open rate. When a customer opens your email, the image is loaded. This
   counts as an open. (Don‚Äôt worry‚Äîthe tracking pixel doesn‚Äôt alter your
   carefully planned designs!)

   Let‚Äôs dig into the data:

Top 10 Email Clients

   Apple iPhone holds the top spot with 33.69% of all opens, with Gmail
   coming in a distant second at 15.96%.
   nov16emailmarketshare.005

Discover your top 10

   When it comes to email marketing, it‚Äôs all about your audience. Use
   Litmus Email Analytics to discover which email clients are most popular
   with your subscribers. Sign up free!

   Discover your audience ‚Üí


iPad Growth Holds, Android Drops for Mobile

   nov16emailmarketshare.002

   While mobile dropped to 55%, it may be a regular fluctuation. Mobile
   market share oscillated between 56% and 55% share since July 2016.
   However, the drop was a surprise since Black Friday mobile sales broke
   records this month. Since many major retailers offered special
   mobile-only deals, it may be that those deals were promoted in-app,
   instead of via email. Either way, Black Friday mobile sales topped $1
   billion‚Äîmobile is still king.

   Last month‚Äôs trends continue this month, with Apple iPad holding at
   12.4%, its highest point since February 2015. Before last month, iPad
   hadn‚Äôt been above 12% since January 2016. This growth may signal that
   iPad users may be replacing their laptop or desktop with an iPad, at
   least for email.

   Android continues to drop, down to 8.56% total opens, almost a 1%
   decrease since last month (when Android also dropped 1%).

   This drop may be due to users switching ship from Android‚Äôs native
   email app to Gmail. Recent changes like the ‚ÄúGmailify‚Äù feature that
   allows users to obtain an email address without ‚Äú@gmail.com‚Äù may appeal
   to Android‚Äôs user base. In addition, Gmail now supports responsive
   design‚Äîholdouts turned off by a poor user experience from
   non-responsive emails in the past may now be switching.

Desktop Drops to 16%

   nov16emailmarketshare.003

   Desktop opens dropped to 16% this month, its lowest ever. Desktop has
   been trending downwards since May 2016 and we may see additional drops
   as mobile and webmail become the choice for email users.

   Outlook remains in the top 10 at 6.05% of market share despite dropping
   steadily since August 2016. And while Outlook may account for a low
   overall percentage of email client market share, it‚Äôs important to know
   what percentage of your audience is opening there‚Äîespecially because
   Outlook can give email geeks headaches.

   Here are a few things to be aware of when coding emails for Outlook:
     * To properly structure your emails for maximum
       cross-device/client/browser render-ability, you‚Äôll need to use
       tables.
     * Outlook doesn‚Äôt support animated GIFs‚Äîit will only show the first
       frame.
     * To make background images work, Outlook requires the use of VML
     * Outlook has no padding support on p, div, and a tags

   There is hope, email geeks. We‚Äôve partnered with Microsoft to
   prioritize email rendering bugs in Outlook, identify issues faster, and
   announce improvements and fixes to the community. You can submit
   Outlook bugs here.

Webmail Opens Grow to 29%

   nov16emailmarketshare.004

   The main driver of webmail growth? Gmail.

   Gmail remains the most popular webmail client by far, jumping up from
   15% to 17% this month. While Gmail has been notoriously difficult to
   design and develop for, there‚Äôs hope! The Gmail team recently rolled
   out support responsive design, improved font styling, and CSS for
   accessibility.

   We‚Äôre following this closely on our Gmail live ticker as changes
   continue to roll out this quarter. While that may take some time, this
   month saw the rollout finally hit the Gmail iOS app. All Gmail mobile
   apps now support responsive email. G Suite accounts show the rendering
   update as well.

   If there was ever a time to go for responsive design, it‚Äôs now! We
   define responsive design as using fluid tables, fluid images, and media
   queries to control the layout of an email across different device
   sizes. Get started with our how-to guide.

WHERE DID WE GET ALL THIS DATA?

   This data is derived from over 1 billion opens collected worldwide with
   Litmus Email Analytics between November 1, 2016 and November 30, 2016.
   It highlights worldwide trends across all industries and verticals.
   Some email clients may be over- or under-represented due to image
   blocking. Tracking trends over time is the best way to monitor open
   data for email!

WHICH EMAIL CLIENTS ARE MOST POPULAR WITH YOUR AUDIENCE?

   While general email client open data is great for looking at trends,
   it‚Äôs your audience that matters. With the addition of a small tracking
   code to your campaigns, Litmus Email Analytics generates a report of
   where your subscribers open your emails. Use that data to focus your
   testing efforts‚Äîand ensure your campaigns look great in inboxes where
   your subscribers are opening.
   Try Litmus free!

